properties.Title: Rainfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Total rainfall amounts of 25 to 35 mm expected. Hazards: 25 to 35 mm of rain. Timing: Rain at times heavy, will end early this evening. Discussion: Low pressure from Texas will track across Lake Huron and Georgian Bay this evening bringing a widespread general rainfall of 25 to 35 mm. The ground, already near saturation and snow covered in many areas, has little ability to absorb further rainfall. Freezing rain is possible over higher elevation areas. For information concerning flooding, please consult your local Conservation Authority or Ontario Ministry of Natural Resources and Forestry District office. Visit Ontario.ca/floods for the latest details. ### Localized flooding in low-lying areas is possible. Be prepared for winter conditions at higher elevations. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Prolonged snowfall event expected beginning this evening. Several hours of freezing rain possible overnight for south-central New Brunswick. Total snowfall: 10 to 15 cm, locally 20 cm. Total Freezing rain: 2 to 5 mm. Maximum wind gusts: 40 to 60 km/h. Locations for snowfall: most of New Brunswick. Locations for freezing rain: south-central New Brunswick. Time span: tonight through Sunday night for snowfall and overnight into early Sunday morning for freezing rain. Remarks: Snow has begun over parts of western New Brunswick this evening and will spread eastward tonight, with strong winds and local blowing snow possible. South-central New Brunswick could see several hours of freezing rain before the change over to rain. Coastal regions along the Fundy shore should remain warm enough for rain with this system. A slight change in the track of the system could affect the snowfall amounts and the duration of freezing rain. The rain-snow line may shift slightly and warnings for snowfall and freezing rain may be required as this system draws nearer. Conditions will improve across the Maritimes on Monday. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NBstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NBStorm.

The heaviest snow is expected this evening. Discussion: A low pressure system from Texas will cross Central Ontario tonight then to Southwestern Quebec Sunday morning, bringing a classic snowstorm with it. The heaviest snow will be this evening with snowfall rates of 2 to 3 cm per hour expected. Brisk northeast winds to 60 km/h will combine with fresh snow to create blowing and drifting snow, particularly in exposed areas. Freezing rain may appear briefly as far north as a line from Bayfield Inlet to Algonquin Park. ### Rapidly accumulating snow will make travel difficult. Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots may become difficult to navigate due to accumulating snow. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.
